  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Neurally adjusted ventilatory assist (NAVA) is a new mode of mechanical ventilation that
      delivers ventilatory assist in proportion to neural effort. It was a controlled randomized
      single-center prospective study in order to explore the efficacy of this new mode of
      mechanical ventilation after corrective open-heart surgery for congenital heart disease.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
  <detailed_description>
    <textblock>
      1. To evaluate the effect of the patient-ventilator interaction in children underwent
           open-heart surgery when ventilated with NAVA, compared with conventional mechanical
           ventilation.

        2. To verify the benefits of NAVA in improving the gas exchange and hemodynamics after
           biventricle repair for CHD.
    </textblock>
  </detailed_description>
